{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 18:22:40.812493", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Diagnostic report — multi‑tier Clos (fat‑tree) EBGP lab\n\nSummary\n- Overall connectivity: Functional. All hosts (pc_*) can reach each other with 0% packet loss in the reachability test.\n- Control plane: FRR BGP sessions are established across the fabric and routes for all /24 host subnets (10.<pod>.<leaf>.0/24) are being advertised and installed on routers.\n- Abnormal behavior detected: Elevated latency and large jitter (high rtt mdev) seen consistently for traffic to/from host pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2). No packet loss observed.\n\nEvidence / Observations\n1) Host reachability (selected, from get_reachability):\n- pc_1_2 -> pc_0_1 (10.0.1.2): tx 4 rx 4 loss 0%, rtt_avg 8.148 ms, rtt_mdev 7.287 ms (rtt_max 20.714 ms)\n- pc_0_1 -> pc_0_0 (10.0.0.2): tx 4 rx 4 loss 0%, rtt_avg 7.35 ms, rtt_mdev 8.168 ms (rtt_max 21.486 ms)\n- pc_0_1 -> pc_0_2 (10.0.2.2): tx 4 rx 4 loss 0%, rtt_avg 7.353 ms, rtt_mdev 8.806 ms (rtt_max 22.602 ms)\n- By contrast, many other host-to-host flows show rtt_avg ~1–3 ms and very small rtt_mdev (<1 ms).\n\nInterpretation: connectivity is correct but latency and jitter are anomalously high specifically for the 10.0.1.0/24 host (pc_0_1).\n\n2) BGP / routing state (from FRR show commands):\n- BGP sessions are UP on all routers involved (super spine, spines, leaves). Example:\n  - super_spine_router_0: 8 neighbors, sessions up (Up/Down times ~00:00:55), routes for 10.0.0.0/24–10.0.3.0/24 and 10.1.0.0/24–10.1.3.0/24 present.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 (AS 65201): is advertising network 10.0.1.0/24 (seen in its running-config) and its BGP session(s) to spines are established (PfxSnt/PfxRcd values present).\n- Routing tables show next-hops are being learned and selected; no obvious BGP route withdraws or missing prefixes.\n\n3) Local interface/address counters and routes for leaf_router_0_1 (ip/ifconfig snapshot)\n- Interfaces and relevant addresses:\n  - eth4: 10.0.1.1/24 (LAN toward pc_0_1)\n  - eth0: 172.16.0.35/31 (uplink)\n  - eth1..eth3: other interconnect /31s\n- ifconfig counters (leaf_router_0_1):\n  - eth0: RX packets 62 bytes 5.4 KiB; TX packets 110,745 bytes 159.8 MiB\n  - eth4: RX packets 110,725 bytes 167.6 MiB; TX packets 41 bytes 3.4 KiB\n  (eth0 shows very large TX; eth4 shows very large RX counters)\n- ip route on leaf_router_0_1 shows other /24s learned via 172.16.0.34 (i.e., neighbor spine next‑hop).\n\nInterpretation: the leaf (leaf_router_0_1) is forwarding substantial traffic between its LAN (eth4) and the uplink (eth0); counters indicate a heavy flow of packets on these interfaces and asymmetry in RX/TX counts per interface view.\n\nLocalization (where the problem is concentrated)\n- The latency/jitter anomaly localizes to the pod containing 10.0.1.0/24 — specifically to leaf_router_0_1 and its uplink to the spine (interfaces eth4 <-> eth0 on leaf_router_0_1 and the peer interface 172.16.0.34 on the adjacent spine).\n- Rationale:\n  - Only traffic to/from 10.0.1.2 exhibits large jitter while other hosts show normal low-latency behaviour.\n  - leaf_router_0_1 interface counters show a large volume of packets on eth0 and eth4, consistent with high utilization on the path that serves 10.0.1.0/24.\n  - Routing/BGP is otherwise converged and stable, so the issue is not a control-plane route loss but a dataplane performance anomaly centered on that leaf/uplink.\n\nRoot cause hypothesis(s)\n(We are identifying likely root causes based on observed evidence; not prescribing fixes.)\n1) Local uplink congestion / queuing on leaf_router_0_1 uplink (eth0) or on the adjacent spine interface (172.16.0.34):\n   - High interface TX/RX counters on leaf_router_0_1 suggest heavy traffic flow across the leaf uplink, which can cause queuing delays and increased jitter for flows to/from 10.0.1.2.\n2) Asymmetric/ECMP forwarding across multiple spine paths with differing latencies:\n   - If traffic to/from 10.0.1.0/24 is ECMP’d across multiple spines (or occasionally traverses the super-spine), some paths may be longer or more congested, producing intermittent high RTTs and large variance.\n3) Microbursts or transient load from a host or traffic generator on that leaf:\n   - The large bytes counters could be from a sustained or bursty flow originated or terminated at pc_0_1 (or another host communicating with it), producing momentary spikes in latency/jitter observable in short ping samples.\n4) Less likely from the data collected: BGP instability or route flapping — BGP sessions are up and prefixes are stable in the sampled outputs.\n\nOther noteworthy findings\n- BGP is established across all expected adjacencies (super-spine ↔ spines ↔ leaves). Prefixes for all /24s are present in routers’ RIBs and FIBs.\n- No packet loss was detected during the ping tests; the issue is performance (latency/jitter) rather than reachability.\n\nSuggested follow-up data collection (diagnostic, not remediation)\n- Gather per‑interface utilization over time (bytes/sec, txqueuelen/queue drops) on leaf_router_0_1 eth0 and the corresponding spine interface (172.16.0.34) to confirm congestion.\n- Collect tc queue statistics and drops on the leaf uplink.\n- If ECMP is in use, check hash-based path selection and compare latency on each path to identify differing path latencies.\n- Capture short packet traces or continuous ping/iperf to quantify jitter and correlate with traffic bursts.\n\nConclusion\n- Network control plane and basic reachability are healthy; however, a localized dataplane performance problem (increased latency and jitter) affects traffic to/from 10.0.1.0/24 (pc_0_1).\n- The most likely root cause is uplink congestion or path asymmetry involving leaf_router_0_1 and its peer spine (172.16.0.34).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 13994, "output_tokens": 4149, "total_tokens": 18143, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 